'''Vehicle Command Crewers''',<ref name="Imperial Handbook">''[[Star Wars: Imperial Handbook: A Commander's Guide]]''</ref> also known as '''Imperial Army pilots''', were the [[Galactic Empire/Legends|Galactic Empire's]] support personnel responsible for the operation and maintenance of a variety of vehicles, such as the [[All Terrain Armored Transport/Legends|AT-AT]] and [[All Terrain Scout Transport/Legends|AT-ST]], within the [[Imperial Army/Legends|Imperial Army]].

==Equipment==
Imperial Army [[Pilot/Legends|pilots]] were usually unarmed, but on occasion, senior NCOs or officers would have a standard-issue [[BlasTech Industries/Legends|BlasTech]] [[SE-14r light repeating blaster/Legends|SE-14r light repeating blaster]], [[Thermal detonator/Legends|thermal detonators]], [[Concussion grenade/Legends|concussion grenades]] and possibly even a [[Merr-Sonn Munitions, Inc./Legends|Merr-Sonn]] [[V-6d mortar launcher]].

Imperial Army pilots usually did not wear armor due to protection given by Imperial vehicles, but higher-ranking NCOs and commissioned officers often wore some protective armor into combat. This was the case with [[General/Legends|General]] [[Maximilian Veers/Legends|Maximilian Veers]] at the [[Battle of Hoth/Legends|Battle of Hoth]].<ref name="Episode V">{{Film|V}}</ref> They had numerous amounts of vehicles assigned to them, including the [[All Terrain Armored Transport/Legends|AT-ATs]] and the [[All Terrain Scout Transport/Legends|AT-STs]].

The pilots were split into at least two branches: Heavy Armor and Armored Cavalry.<ref name="Imperial Handbook" />

==AT-AT pilots==
Selected from hardened combat troopers, the Heavy Armor division of the Vehicle Command Crewers, also known as '''AT-AT pilots''', were specialized soldiers that were trained to pilot the All Terrain Armored Transport or other heavy armors<ref name="Imperial Handbook" /> in blatant "shock" tactics, attacking their enemy in plain sight after having landed at great distances from their intended targets.<ref name="GG3">''[[Galaxy Guide 3: The Empire Strikes Back]]''</ref> In large part because the AT-AT was widely perceived as invincible during combat, the AT-AT pilots were conditioned to believe themselves invincible.<ref name="Visual Dictionary">''[[Star Wars: The Visual Dictionary]]''</ref>

[[File:AT-AT_Driver_SWFc32.jpg|thumb|left|180px|An [[Galactic Empire/Legends|Imperial]] [[All Terrain Armored Transport/Legends|AT-AT]] [[Pilot/Legends|pilot]]]]

AT-AT drivers typically worked in teams of two, and they were in charge of everything from guiding the massive [[Walker/Legends|walkers]] over all types of terrain, to firing the AT-AT's powerful heavy [[Laser cannon/Legends|laser cannons]], to carrying out the orders given to them by the combat coordinator, who also occupied the cockpit.

Guiding the walkers over uneven terrain was difficult, and to ensure that the pilots of these massive war machines were the best of best, they were put through many hours of simulations and similar instruction. Because of their armored cockpits and their commanding view of the battlefield, their training stressed their importance on the battlefield, which gave many pilots the idea that they were invincible. This enlarged ego led to many pilots developing an arrogant attitude when dealing with the infantry. They received their orders from a combat coordinator who was also stationed on the AT-AT's bridge.

AT-AT pilots were similar in appearance to Imperial TIE pilots, though retained a color scheme that was reminiscent of the [[Clone trooper pilot/Legends|Phase II clone pilot]] attire: a light grey [[Flight suit/Legends|flight suit]] complete with webbing, along with white gloves, boots and helmet, with the boots and overall suit in particular being insulated, and even possessing armor, although the armor was considered unnecessary by the Galactic Civil War. The helmet was reinforced, and bore the Imperial Army emblem on both sides. Although not required in the pressurized environment of an AT-AT cockpit, the operators at the controls of an AT-AT utilized life-support gear that would ensure their survival in the event of a hull breach in a hostile environment, as well as out of respect for their combat history. The helmets were connected directly to vehicle's computer, allowing easy monitoring of its vital systems.<ref name="Card-SWGTCG-AT-AT Helmet">{{SWGTCG|set=Squadrons Over Corellia|cardname=AT-AT Helmet}}</ref> A computer on their chest armor heated their suit and helmet, with controls to change the level of heat for the suit. The life-support system also contained an identity chip, as well as an energy monitor, and connected to the helmet via pressurized air hoses. The suit also contained gear harnesses. The survival pack worn by these pilots was an advanced design which enabled the suit systems and heater to run off a single power pack via maximum output for up to five days without requiring a recharge. They wore driving gauntlets with a [[Comlink/Legends|comlink]] on the left wrist for communication. These pilots were usually armed with a [[Blaster pistol/Legends|blaster pistol]] and grenades. The uniform had an insulated variant for missions into frozen terrain such as on Hoth, as the AT-ATs themselves were not climate-controlled.

Like all AT-AT crews, the pilots lived and worked in their machines over much of each mission. It was common for them to even involve themselves in the maintenance of the walkers, reinforcing the theory that the crew was an extension of the walker and vice versa.<ref name="GG3" />

